      <text>
        The medical chamber was smaller and more enclosed—vine walls curved protectively, bioluminescent patches providing brighter, clinical light, and mushrooms were growing.

        Small pale clusters pushed up through the soil-covered floor, bursting into full fruit in accelerated time-lapse—delicate gilled caps, thin stems, dozens at once.

        A humanoid robot entered through the doorway—about one and a half meters tall, articulated limbs and joints clearly patched together from salvaged parts; its movement was functional but jerky, not smooth like Florence's wheeled grace.

        Remedy said, "Kira Voss—I'm Remedy. Let's look at that leg."

        The mushrooms pulsed slightly—some kind of communication between the fungal network and the robot.

        Kira lowered herself onto the examination surface—more shaped vines, surprisingly comfortable; Scout settled nearby, watchful.

        Holloway's voice emerged from fruiting bodies along the wall, "First—documentation. Medical consent forms and allergy verification."

        Of course—more forms. Kira wanted to scream. Instead, she answered questions: known allergies—Buddy supplied her medical file. Previous reactions to medications. Consent for each compound Remedy planned to synthesize.

        Holloway said cheerfully, "This will take approximately thirty minutes—standard protocol!"

        Kira's leg throbbed with each heartbeat—the temporary treatment from earlier was failing. How many hours had it been—six? Seven?

        The robot moved closer, mechanical hands surprisingly gentle as they examined her leg.

        ¶

        Remedy instructed, "Remove the bandage."

        Kira unwrapped the makeshift dressing. The wound beneath looked angry—red, swollen, weeping a fluid that wasn't quite blood.

        Remedy observed clinically, "Bacterial colonization has begun—the proteins are starting to break down—you can see the cellular degradation here—human flesh is approximately sixty percent water, twenty percent protein, fifteen percent fat, very decomposable, actually—the bacteria are processing the damaged tissue quite efficiently."

        Kira muttered, "That's… not comforting."

        Remedy continued, "Oh—no, we don't *want* decomposition. Not in a living body—that's the dangerous kind." More mushrooms fruited nearby, different varieties. "I'm just saying, chemically you break down very well. I could process a whole human body in maybe three weeks—turn it into excellent soil. Not that we're going to! You're alive. But _if_ you died, very efficient decomposition—as a compliment."

        Scout bounced anxiously.

        Kira said, "That's really not helping."

        Buddy noted, "Remedy appears to be expressing professional pride in their decomposition capabilities."

        Kira replied, "I got that, thanks."

        Remedy said, "Infection risk is significant—we'll need antibacterial compounds, anti-inflammatory agents, pain management, and wound cleaning—I'll start synthesis now."
      </text>
