        More mushrooms grew—different shapes, sizes, colors. The robot moved between them, harvesting caps and extracting fluids into salvaged containers.

        Holloway, from the wall, said, "Each compound requires separate consent."

        Kira said—her voice cracking—"Fine. Yes. Whatever you need—please… fix it."

        The pain was constant now: sharp when she moved, throbbing when still. Hours of bureaucracy, forms, training, and exhaustion piled on top of the injury.

        Remedy said—direct but not unkind—"I understand. The chemistry takes time, but it works—I'm very good at chemistry."

        The synthesis began.

        Remedy explained each step—growing specific mushroom varieties, extracting compounds, testing pH levels, and documenting concentrations. The robot manipulated equipment with mechanical precision. Mushrooms fruited, were harvested, decomposed back into the network, and new varieties emerged.

        Remedy said, holding up a small white mushroom, "This one produces the antibacterial compound—breaks down bacterial cell walls. Very effective against the species colonizing your wound. The molecules bind to—"

        Kira interrupted, "I trust you." She was too tired for chemistry lessons.

        Remedy continued processing. "Right. Yes. Chemistry works whether you understand it or not—that's what I like about it. Honest. Unlike bureaucracy."

        Despite everything, Kira almost smiled.

        Time blurred. The robot worked steadily, occasionally sprouting new fruiting bodies for different compounds. Holloway's voice provided updates on documentation status. Scout bounced supportively. Buddy offered medical data from her files.

        Kira waited, in pain, exhausted.

        ¶

        Finally—after what felt like another eternity but was probably two hours—Remedy approached with several prepared compounds.

        Remedy announced, "Ready to begin treatment."

        Holloway confirmed, "All consents documented and filed."

        The robot's hands were surprisingly gentle as they cleaned the wound with a solution that stung but felt purposeful. Then came antibacterial compounds—cool gel from the extracted mushroom chemistry.

        Remedy said, "This will prevent further bacterial decomposition—kills the colonizing species, lets your body's natural processes handle the damaged tissue. Much better than external decomposition."

        Kira observed, "You really love talking about decomposition."

        Remedy replied, *"It's what I do! Breaking things down, transforming them into something useful—dead cells become nutrients, nutrients become new growth. It's beautiful, chemically speaking."*

        The treatment continued—anti-inflammatory compounds, pain management, more cleaning. The robot worked methodically, checking concentrations, documenting application, and ensuring proper coverage.

        And slowly—wonderfully—the pain began to recede. Not gone entirely, but reduced. Manageable.
      </text>
