        The sharp edge dulled and the throbbing eased.

        Kira felt tears prick her eyes and blinked them away.

        Remedy said.
        "The compounds are working — your inflammatory response is decreasing — the bacterial colonization is halted — the wound should heal properly now — excellent chemistry."

        Kira said.
        "Thank you."

        Remedy's voice carried something like pleasure.

        Remedy said.
        "Though I am glad you're not decomposing — much better to have living humans than dead ones — even if dead ones make very rich soil."

        Scout bounced approvingly.

        Fresh bandages were applied — soft material Remedy said came from processed plant fibers, clean and sterile, properly secured.

        Remedy said.
        "You'll need to rest now — let the compounds work, let your body heal — I'll fruit antibacterial mushrooms daily for wound care — maybe a week until full recovery."

        Kira repeated.
        "Rest."
        The word sounded impossibly good.

        Holloway said via the wall fruiting bodies.
        "We've assigned you temporary quarters — Scout will show you the way!"

        Scout bounced toward another doorway immediately.

        Kira stood. Her leg still hurt, but it was bearable now — she could walk without wanting to scream.

        The robot watched her.
        "Human bodies are remarkable, actually — self-healing, adaptive — much more interesting alive than dead — though both are valid states, chemically."

        Kira said dryly.
        "I'll try to stay in the alive state."

        "Excellent plan! Much less decomposition involved," the robot said.

        The quarters were small — another vine-formed chamber with soft groundcover, dim bioluminescence, surprisingly private. Scout bounced in circles, making sure she saw the water source (a spring flowing through shaped vines), the waste facilities, and the sleeping space of soft moss and woven plant fibers.

        Kira sank down onto the sleeping surface.

        Her whole body ached and her mind felt like static. She'd been through a crash, injury, a walk through an alien forest, intake forms, four hours of workplace safety training, medical documentation, and treatment.

        One endless day on an alien planet with bureaucratic plants — and somehow she'd survived it.

        Scout pressed against her hand — warm, solid, comforting.

        Kira whispered.
        "Thank you — for everything."

        Scout bounced once, then settled nearby, keeping watch.

        The bioluminescence dimmed further, responding to her exhaustion somehow.

        Kira closed her eyes.

        They had helped. It had taken forever, filtered through absurd procedures, involved workplace harassment policies and decomposition commentary, but they had genuinely helped.

        She was alive. Treated. Safe.

        ¶

        For now, that was enough.

        Sleep pulled her down like gravity.

        She surrendered to it gratefully.
      </text>
